body:
Hello,

I would like to be able to parameterise structs, and pass them to a generic module as a type parameter.

From my understanding packages cannot be parameterised, so I need to put the typedef either in a class or in an interface.

However, from what I gather verilator does not allow to access typedefs within an interface. But classes should work.

So what's up with the following?

What would be the intended way to achieve this?

```
class pipeline_class #(
    parameter int XLEN = 32,
    localparam type XWORD = logic [XLEN-1:0],
    localparam type RADDR = logic [$clog2(XLEN)-1:0]
);
  // IF -> ID
  typedef struct packed {XWORD pc;} if_id_t;

  /* ... */

endclass

module pipe_reg #(
    parameter type T = logic,
    parameter T CLR_VAL = 1'b0
) (
    input logic clk,
    input logic en,
    input logic clr,
    input T din,
    output T dout
);

  /* ... */

endmodule

module fred #(
    localparam int XLEN = 32,
    localparam int ILEN = 32,
    localparam type XWORD = logic [XLEN-1:0]
) (
    input  logic clk,
    input  logic rst,
    output XWORD a0
);

  /* ... */

  // IF -> ID
  typedef struct packed {XWORD pc;} if_id_t;

  pipe_reg #(pipeline_class #()::if_id_t) if_id_reg (
      /* ... */
  );

  /* ... */

endmodule
```

Gives error:

```
%Error: rtl/fred.sv:34:34: Expecting expression to be constant, but can't convert a DOT to constant.
                         : ... note: In instance 'fred'
   34 |   pipe_reg #(pipeline_class #()::if_id_t) if_id_reg (
      |                                  ^~~~~~~
        ... See the manual at https://verilator.org/verilator_doc.html?v=5.040 for more assistance.
%Error: rtl/fred.sv:34:34: Parameter type pin value isn't a type: Param '__paramNumber1' of 'if_id_reg'
                         : ... note: In instance 'fred'
   34 |   pipe_reg #(pipeline_class #()::if_id_t) if_id_reg (
      |                                  
```

What 'verilator' command line do we use to run your example?

```
verilator --binary --top-module fred rtl/yadayadayada
```

What 'verilator --version' are you using?  Did you try it with the git master version?  Did you try it with other simulators?

```
Verilator 5.040 2025-08-30 rev v5.040
```

